    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="370"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d370">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 339.41/1.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 28, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have received a telegram from
                    Sir Edward Grey instructing me to convey the thanks of His Majesty’s Government
                    to the United States Government for the courtesy and good will displayed by them
                    in issuing orders<note n="9" xml:id="d370fn9">In pursuance of a telephonic
                        request made by the British Embassy on April 25.</note> to the United States
                    ship <pb facs="0378" n="262" xml:id="pg_262"/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Wheeling</hi>, proceeding to Santo Domingo, to protect British
                    subjects as well as American citizens.</p>
                <p>It gives me much pleasure to be the bearer of this message.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>P. S. April 29. I have just heard from your Department that owing to
                        interruption of the cable the <hi rend="italic">Petrel</hi> has been sent to
                        Santo Domingo instead of the <hi rend="italic">Wheeling</hi>. I have
                        informed Sir E. Grey accordingly.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>C. S. R.</signed>
                    </closer>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
